│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                      │
│ I have found the code. It's different from what I remembered from newer LLVM versions, but the logic is the same.            │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ 506       // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift amount, set is_zero_poison to true.                                        │
│ 507       if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&                                                                      │
│ 508           match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))))                                                    │
│ 509         return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1, IC.Builder.getTrue());                                                           │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ This code block checks if the `cttz` intrinsic has one use, if its `is_zero_poison` argument (`Op1`) is false (`m_Zero()`),  │
│ and if that single use is a shift instruction. If all conditions are met, it replaces the `is_zero_poison` argument with     │
│ `true`. This is the buggy transformation. The original reproducer has `noundef` on the `cttz` call, which means it can't be  │
│ poison. The transform changes `cttz(y, false)` to `cttz(y, true)`. If `y` is 0, the first returns `bitwidth`, the second     │
│ returns `poison`. The `noundef` on the original call is violated by the transformation. The `hasOneUse()` check is also      │
│ weaker than the `AllUsesAreShifts` loop I was expecting, but it's the same idea.                                             │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ To fix the issue, I will comment out lines 507, 508, and 509.                                                                │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                      │
│ sed -i -e '507,509s/^/\/\/ /' ./llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp                                         │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
